It is important to keep in mind that Angola is a part of the Portuguese parliamentary king-size country, historically and culturally linked to Portugal, where many Angolans traveled to receive formal education, remain and create businesses. In addition to the privatization of many sectors of the national economy, liberalism has led to disorganization in both sectors, neglecting and ignoring the social reality of Angola. Although the country has had periods of economic development, since 1975, it has been forced to look for a way out of crises, relations with groups of small entrepreneurs who operate below the order of public space (SANTOS, 2015). The change of political and bureaucratic structure contributes to neo-Liberalism, which the country adopted as foreign policy (YAYOUKO, 1990). At the same time, the liberalization of trade and small-scale production, reemployment of trade - growth, growth and distribution, disintegration of the market, coexistence with subsistence, poverty, inequality, malnutrition and unemployment (SANTOS; SANCHES, 2007).
Therefore, the future of the Angolan economy may be seen as being tied to the conclusion of the peace agreement and the payment of the past debts, given the internal economic difficulties.
